# Next.js Best Practices (Flow)

## Server Components by Default

- All pages and data-fetching components should be Server Components unless they need interactivity
- Add `"use client"` only when the component uses hooks, event handlers, or browser APIs
- Fetch data in Server Components, pass as props to Client Components

## Data Fetching

- Fetch data in Server Components — use `Promise.all` for parallel requests, never sequential
- Export `dynamic = "force-dynamic"` on pages with auth checks or real-time data
- Do NOT use `unstable_cache` for data — causes stale data that's hard to debug

## Bundle Optimization

- **Lazy-load Recharts** when charts aren't the primary view. Use dynamic import with a `rc` state variable:
  ```typescript
  const [rc, setRc] = useState<typeof import("recharts") | null>(null);
  useEffect(() => { import("recharts").then(setRc); }, []);
  ```
  Then use `rc.BarChart`, `rc.LineChart`, etc. Never bare imports when lazy-loading.
- Use `next/dynamic` for heavy client components that aren't needed on initial render
- Keep page-level Server Components lean — push complexity into child components

## Component Patterns

- **Suspense boundaries** around async content with `<DashboardSkeleton>` fallbacks
- **Error boundaries** for graceful failure on data-fetch errors
- Colocate data fetching with the component that uses it (not in parent pages)
- Extract reusable UI into `components/ui/` with consistent Flow styling

## Styling

- Tailwind CSS for all styling. Use Flow brand tokens:
  - `bg-[#F3EDDF]` (Moonlight), `text-[#3D3D3D]` (Midnight), `bg-[#E89700]` (Sunlight)
  - White cards: `bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm`
- Prefer Tailwind classes over inline styles or CSS modules
- Mobile-first: design for mobile, enhance for desktop

## Performance

- Minimize client-side JavaScript. Prefer server rendering.
- Use `loading.tsx` files for route-level loading states
- Images: use `next/image` with proper `width`/`height` or `fill` prop
- Avoid layout shifts: set explicit dimensions on containers before data loads

## API Routes

- Use Route Handlers (`app/api/`) for server-side logic
- Protect with `CRON_SECRET` for cron endpoints
- Return proper HTTP status codes and structured JSON errors
- For heavy computation, consider Edge Runtime (but verify compatibility first)

## Common Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- Fetching data in `useEffect` when a Server Component would work
- Importing full libraries client-side when only a subset is needed
- Using `any` types — prefer proper TypeScript types from `lib/types/`
- Nesting Suspense boundaries unnecessarily (one per major data section is enough)
- Creating API routes just to fetch data — use Server Components directly when possible
